hing about what the white-collar workforce should expect to see in the years ahead, as job-killing technologies and the shipping of work overseas take away even more good jobs.  Cut Loose offers a poignant look at how the long-term unemployed struggle in today’s unfair economy to support their families, rebuild their lives, and overcome the shame and self-blame they deal with on a daily basis. It is also a call to action—a blueprint for a new kind of politics, one that offers a measure of grace in a society of ruthless advancement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAutomobile industry workerszCanadavCase studies. 0aAutomobile industry workerszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aUnemployedzCanada. 0aUnemployedzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  a21st century american economy.  aamerican auto industry.  aamerican economy.  aamerican history.  aauto industry.  aautoworkers.  abusiness.  acall to action.  acar industry.  aclass inequality.  adepressed economy.  aeconomic concerns.  aeconomy.  aethics.  afactory work.  agreat recession.  ahistorical.  aincome inequality.  aindustrial economic relations.  ajob killing technology.  alabor policy.  alabor.  alaid off workers.  amiddle class.  amorality.  apolitical.  apolitics.  asociology.  atechnology.  aunemployment.  awork overseas.  aworker.  aworking class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028300840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095885240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958852423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958852/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO